\begin_layout Section
Forest Fire Danger Index and fire weather variability 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section described synoptic patterns linked to fire activity.
 Fire weather indices offer a complementary approach to fire research.
 These indices quantify the risk that weather conditions pose to fire occurrence
 and behaviour.
 They are also useful metrics to assess the changes in fire danger over
 extended periods of time.
 The use of the McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index (FFDI) has been common
 in Australia (citation).
 Therefore, this section reviews the literature that evaluated fire weather
 variability using this index.
 Although, some results are contrasted with global and regional investigations
 that used alternative indices.
 An analysis of fire weather projections complements this discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI has been the basis to understand fire weather in Australia.
 Willimas and Karoly (1999) found that “El Nino” events increase fire danger
 in central and eastern Australia.
 Using the FFDI, Long (2006) found that extreme events in Victoria occurred
 with a wind flowing from the north or north-west.
 This result is consistent with the results discussed in the previous section.
 Lucas (2010) developed a historical database of FFDI values.
 This study computed FFDI from weather stations across the country for the
 period 1973-2008.
 Clarke at al.
 (2013) simulated fire weather spatial distribution in southeastern Australia.
 The authors used the Weather Reasearch and Forecasting (WRF) model (citation)
 for the period 1985-2009.
 They found that WFR was suitable to provide spatially continuous fire weather
 information in this region.
 However, the development of a global fire weather dataset have provided
 an alternative source of continuous fire weather data for this region (Field
 et al.
 2009).
 This section of the review provides particular attention to the analysis
 of FFDI trends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fire weather in southeastern Australia has become more dangerous.
 Lucas et al.
 (2007) investigated fire weather recent trends in southeast Australia.
 They found that there were significant positive trends in several metrics
 of FFDI.
 Clarke et al.
 (2012) agree with these results.
 In this study, the authors built on the work of Lucas (2010) calculating
 the FFDI in more stations, extending the period of analysis, and homogenizing
 wind speed data for the computations.
 Clarke et al.
 (2012) analyzed trends with FFDI metrics and found that there are significant
 increases in fire danger in Australia-especially in the southeast of the
 continent.
 Fire weather variability before the nineteen-seventies has not been investigate
d in this region.
 Extending this record would provide valuable information about past fire
 weather changes.
 However, this research remains a challenge due to the lack of weather stations
 records.
 Using reanalysis products could be an alternative approach to address this
 problem.
 In contrast, the investigation of future fire weather has received more
 research attention.
\end_layout

