\begin_layout Standard
As shown in this review most studies use the FFDI to describe fire weather
 in this region.
 Despite its acceptance by the scientific community, the FFDI has significant
 shortcomings.
 First of all, empirical research is the basis of this index.
 Therefore, its equation may not represent the actual physical relationship
 between them.
 The index does not consider the influence of topography on fire weather.
 Additionally, the calibration of the FFDI considered the vegetation characteris
tics of southeastern Australia.
 Therefore, it may not represent fire conditions in other regions of the
 continent.
 Even the language of its fire danger ratings have also been questioned.
 According to the VBRC the FFDI failed to represent the specific extreme
 nature of “Black Saturday” (VBRC, 2010).
 Moreover, this report suggests to develop a new index.
 However, proposals for a new Australian fire weather index have not been
 published in the scientific literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The criticisms to the FFDI have been balanced with studies that show its
 efficiency.
 For example, Dowdy et al.
 (2009) presented a comparative study of the FFDI and the widely used Candain
 Fire Weather Index (FWI).
 The investigation mathematically deconstructed the two indices to establish
 comparisons.
 The study found that these two indices offer comparable results in the
 Australian context.
 Albeit its limitations, the FFDI continues to be the stepping stone of
 fire weather research in Australia.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fire weather forecasting and climate modes of variability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the investigations have focused on the sub-regional processes
 that drive fire weather.
 However, climate modes of variability exert a significant influence on
 weather—and fire weather—in Australia.
 For example, “El Nino” events generally bring dry conditions to Australia
 (Risbey, 2009).
 On the other, hand wet conditions are usually linked to a “La Nina” events.
 Moreover, the Indian Ocean dynamics has contributed to several droughts
 in southeastern Australia (citations).
 In fact, positive phases of the Indian Ocean Dipole produce hot and dry
 conditions during in spring in Victoria.
 These environmental conditions contribute to the availability of fuels
 and an increase in extreme fire events in this region (Cai, 2009).
 A large-scale analysis of the weather patterns associated with fire activity
 in this region could offer further insights to disentangle the influences
 of these climate modes of variability over fire weather.
 To accomplish this, a long-term analysis of fire weather is again necessary.
 A synoptic climatology of fire weather could contribute to having greater
 confidence in the global patterns that drive fire weather in this region.
\end_layout

